‚Äã@@smears6039 on eating shellfish, no, it's not. You can read Acts 10 for clarification. As for wearing mixed fibers, there is mountains of nuance here. This is not so much a moral law as it is a social law given specifically to the Israelite people. First, the "mixed" fibers referred to were wool and linen. Only the priests could wear such mixtures (which also shows that the mixture, in and of itself, is not sinful). Therefore, the social law is making clear that there is a distinction to be made, just as we have laws today that say you can't where officer clothing and impersonate a military/police officer. There is much more to be said here, but I won't go too deep because I will assume you don't care much about this nuance. (Feel free to correct me of that assumption.) So the next natural question is, how do we distinguish between social prescriptions and moral absolutes? Common sense, really. Paul gives a great example of this. "For it is written in the Law of Moses: 'Do not muzzle an ox while it is treading out the grain.' (emphasis mine, 1 Cor. 9:9). An atheist would look at this and say, "Ah, so have you muzzled an ox lately? See! You committed a sin." But the law, like all laws, have a spirit to them. Paul uses this social prescription to show that it would be immoral not to support the church's teachers. This spirit-of-the-law point, speaking modernly now, is also why no one would convict a father rushing his wife and child to the ER, though he may have committed countless traffic violations. The spirit of the law, when it comes to traffic violations, is to protect life. Did the father honor the spirit of the law by rushing his wife to the ER? Yes. Again, what about homosexuality? There is nothing in the Bible that explains this as not a sin. There is nothing that homosexuality alludes to in the spirit of the law. And worse, the New Testament still makes clear that this was and still is objectively a sin.
